{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ecb3b89b-19ab-4f69-b284-97dff089155f","content":"The project doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the most common for local servers):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `type: \"stdio\"` — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- `command` / `args` — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, point `command` directly at the executable.\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC messages to **stdout** and logs to **stderr** (not stdout), or Copilot won't be able to parse responses.\n\nAfter saving, restart VS Code or use the **MCP: List Servers** command to pick up the new config.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e4df21de-074c-4cd8-98ab-12b48531f168","outputTokens":292,"requestId":"7016:25EBA9:14372D0:176B446:69EC1166"},"id":"997fd066-fa77-4f42-85ba-e4bb175ba06c","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:57:18.671Z","parentId":"1a70fcd6-1a10-4311-8478-b38f98ffcd68"}
